[3] MA: Bat rabies in Brookline
Date: 28 Jun 2010
Source: Boston.com [edited]
<http://www.boston.com/yourotwn/news/brookline/2010/06/brookline_issues_rabies_adviso.html>


Health officials in Brookline issued a rabies advisory Monday [28 Jun
2010] after a bat captured in the town tested positive for the viral
disease.

The advisory was issued after the Massachusetts Department of Public
Health notified the town Monday [28 Jun 2010] that a bat captured in
Brookline tested positive for rabies, which is fatal if left untreated.

In a press release announcing the advisory, Brookline Chief of
Environmental Health, Pat Maloney, said that if a bat is found
indoors, it should not be released until it can be ruled out that a
pet or person has not been exposed. Bat bites can often go undetected
because there is no visible bite mark or scratch left on the skin by
the bat's small tooth. Health officials said 95 percent of people
infected with rabies during the past 10 years were unaware they had
been bitten or scratched.

If the bat cannot be captured and tested, people who could have been
exposed to a bite or direct contact should be vaccinated, according to
health officials.

Anyone and any pets exposed to bats should be reported to the
Brookline Health Department at 617-730-2300.

[Byline: Brock Parker]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[If you find a dead bat or kill a bat, do not touch it with your bare
hands, use a plastic bag to pick it up and enclose it to take to the
state rabies lab. - Mod.JW]

