[4] LA: Rabies confirmed in Jeff Davis Parish horse
Date: 30 Jun 2010
Source: Louisiana Department of Agriculture & Forestry
<http://www.ldaf.state.la.us/portal/News/PressReleaseCurrent/tabid/92/itemid/1415/Default.aspx>


Agriculture and Forestry Commissioner Mike Strain, D.V.M., said a Jeff
Davis Parish horse was confirmed with rabies on 28 Jun 2010.

The horse, a 6-year-old thoroughbred mare domiciled in the Jennings
area, was brought to the LSU School of Veterinary Medicine in Baton
Rouge on 27 Jun 2010 after exhibiting abnormal facial twitching
symptoms. The neurologic signs worsened, and the horse was
euthanized. A subsequent necropsy verified rabies.

"Rabies signs are often neurological and very similar to other disease
signs like eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) and West Nile virus
(WNV)," Strain said. "All of those diseases affect the brain." Strain
added that relatively few people vaccinate their horses for rabies.
"Horses are mammals, and all mammals can contract rabies. If you're
going to vaccinate your livestock for EEE and West Nile, the cost of
adding a rabies vaccination is minimal. It's a disease that can easily
be prevented."

--
